<!DOCTYPE html><html lang="en"><head><meta charSet="utf-8"/><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width"/><script src="https://cmp.osano.com/AzZdRbSORDOOzF9W/4bef01ac-7309-4ccf-ae6b-742c7d645b33/osano.js" async=""></script><title>Hybrid Fitted Numerical Scheme for Singularly Perturbed Convection-Diffusion Problem with a Small Time Lag</title><meta name="robots" content="index"/><meta name="Author" content="Hindawi"/><meta name="title" content="Hybrid Fitted Numerical Scheme for Singularly Perturbed Convection-Diffusion Problem with a Small Time Lag"/><meta name="description" content="In this article, a singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem with a small time lag is examined. Because of the appearance of a small perturbation parameter, a boundary layer is observed in the solution of the problem. A hybrid scheme has been constructed, which is a combination of the cubic spline method in the boundary layer region and the midpoint upwind scheme in the outer layer region on a piecewise Shishkin mesh in the spatial direction. For the discretization of the time derivative, the Crank-Nicolson method is used. Error analysis of the proposed method has been performed. We found that the proposed scheme is second-order convergent. Numerical examples are given, and the numerical results are in agreement with the theoretical results. Comparisons are made, and the results of the proposed scheme give more accurate solutions and a higher rate of convergence as compared to some previous findings available in the literature."/><meta property="og:url" content="https://www.hindawi.com/journals/aaa/2023/4382780/"/><meta property="og:site_name" content=""/><meta property="og:title" content="Hybrid Fitted Numerical Scheme for Singularly Perturbed Convection-Diffusion Problem with a Small Time Lag"/><meta property="og:type" content="website"/><meta property="og:description" content="In this article, a singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem with a small time lag is examined. Because of the appearance of a small perturbation parameter, a boundary layer is observed in the solution of the problem. A hybrid scheme has been constructed, which is a combination of the cubic spline method in the boundary layer region and the midpoint upwind scheme in the outer layer region on a piecewise Shishkin mesh in the spatial direction. For the discretization of the time derivative, the Crank-Nicolson method is used. Error analysis of the proposed method has been performed. We found that the proposed scheme is second-order convergent. Numerical examples are given, and the numerical results are in agreement with the theoretical results. Comparisons are made, and the results of the proposed scheme give more accurate solutions and a higher rate of convergence as compared to some previous findings available in the literature."/><meta property="og:image:type" content="image/jpeg"/><meta property="og:image:width" content="600"/><meta property="og:image:height" content="315"/><meta name="og:image" content="https://images.hindawi.com/journals/aaa/aaa.banner.jpg"/><meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image"/><meta name="twitter:site" content="website"/><meta name="twitter:description" content="Hybrid Fitted Numerical Scheme for Singularly Perturbed Convection-Diffusion Problem with a Small Time Lag"/><meta name="twitter:title" content="In this article, a singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem with a small time lag is examined. href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-8205-4277" aria-label="Redirect to Doi" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer"><span role="img" class="anticon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 256 186.2H70.9V79.1h15.4v107.1zm22.6-107.1h41.6c39.6 0 57 28.3 57 53.6 0 27.5-21.5 53.6-56.8 53.6h-41.8V79.1zm15.4 93.3h24.5c34.9 0 42.9-26.5 42.9-39.7C191.7 111.2 178 93 148 93h-23.7v79.4zM88.7 56.8c0 class="simpleShowMore__button">Show more</button></div><div class="articleHeader__academicEditor"><strong>Academic Editor: </strong><span>Devendra Kumar</span></div><div class="articleHeader__timeline"><div class="articleHeader__timeline_item "><strong>Received</strong><span>23 Aug 2022</span></div><div class="articleHeader__timeline_item "><strong>Revised</strong><span>02 Feb 2023</span></div><div class="articleHeader__timeline_item "><strong>Accepted</strong><span>27 Mar 2023</span></div><div class="articleHeader__timeline_item articleHeader__timeline_item_sticky"><strong>Published</strong><span>06 Apr 2023</span></div></div></div><div class="articleBody"><div class="xml-content"><h4 class="header" id="abstract">Abstract</h4><p>In this article, a singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem with a small time lag is examined. Because of the appearance of a small perturbation parameter, a boundary layer is observed in the solution of the problem. A hybrid scheme has been constructed, which is a combination of the cubic spline method in the boundary layer region and the midpoint upwind scheme in the outer layer region on a piecewise Shishkin mesh in the spatial direction. For the discretization of the time derivative, the Crank-Nicolson method is used. Error analysis of the proposed method has been performed. We found that the proposed scheme is second-order convergent. Numerical examples are given, and the numerical results are in agreement with the theoretical results. Comparisons are made, and the results of the proposed scheme give more accurate solutions and a higher rate of convergence as compared to some previous findings available in the literature.</p><span class="end-abs"></span><h4 id="introduction">1. Introduction</h4><p>The delay differential equations are versatile in mathematical modeling of processes where they provide a realistic simulation of the real-world phenomena. The real-world operations/interactions that take time to complete can be utilized to simulate the time lag experience such as gestation time, incubation period, and transportation delays. In the model, if a small parameter multiplies the highest order derivative term, involving at least one shift term in the temporal variable, we call it singularly perturbed time delay differential equations (SPTDDE). These problems arise in the varied area of science and engineering models, for instance, in population dynamics, in epidemiology, in respiratory system, and in tumor growth [<a href="#B1">1</a>–<a href="#B6">6</a>]. For more additional models, one can refer [<a href="#B7">7</a>, <a href="#B8">8</a>]. Due to the appearance of the boundary layer in the solution of a singularly perturbed differential equation, classical numerical methods on equidistant grids are inadequate and fail to provide a reliable approximation, when the perturbation parameter tends to zero, unless otherwise, if one uses an unacceptably large number of grid points. Several articles have been written on the solution method for singularly perturbed delay differential equations, to cite a few [<a href="#B9">9</a>–<a href="#B13">13</a>]. Among the recently conducted studies on SPTDDE of the convection-diffusion type, having a right end boundary layer, in [<a href="#B14">14</a>], the authors used an implicit-trapezoidal scheme on uniform mesh for temporal discretization, and for spatial discretization, a hybrid scheme, which is a combination of the midpoint upwind scheme and the central difference scheme on Shishkin type meshes, is applied. In [<a href="#B8">8</a>], the scheme is constructed using the Crank-Nicolson method for temporal discretization, and a midpoint upwind finite difference scheme on a fitted piecewise-uniform mesh in spatial discretization is applied. In [<a href="#B15">15</a>], the scheme is devised using backward Euler’s scheme on uniform mesh for temporal discretization and a new stable finite difference scheme on Shishkin mesh for spatial discretization. In [<a href="#B16">16</a>], the problem is solved using the Crank-Nicolson method in temporal discretization, and in the spatial discretization, an exponentially fitted operator finite difference method on uniform mesh is used. All these developed schemes can work for both small and large time delays. However, except [<a href="#B14">14</a>], the results of the above studies are first-order convergent, and there are some exceptional properties which work only for a small time delay <span class="inline_break"><svg height="11.5564pt" id="M1" style="vertical-align:-2.26807pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -9.28833 22.483 11.5564" width="22.483pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)"><path d="M300 -147C201 -63 143 98 143 270S200 602 300 686L282 710C136 610 70 450 70 271V270C70 89 136 -72 282 -170L300 -147Z" id="g113-41"></path></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,4.498,0)"><path d="M494 514C482 587 419 712 303 712C238 712 174 667 174 603C174 561 205 514 249 449C219 438 187 422 162 407C93 366 23 283 23 177C23 69 87 -12 190 -12C244 -12 288 5 328 33C406 87 444 170 444 249C444 329 404 391 331 475C265 550 222 605 222 627C222 647 238 657 267 657C355 657 421 585 484 499L494 514ZM359 234C359 143 319 30 219 30C172 30 114 75 114 178C114 275 163 343 195 378C212 397 241 415 269 425C305 382 359 313 359 234Z" id="g113-226"></path></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,14.852,0)"><path d="M512 -3V55L134 254V256L512 456V514L75 281V230L512 -3Z" id="g117-91"></path></g></svg><span class="irelop"></span><svg height="11.5564pt" style="vertical-align:-2.26807pt" version="1.1" viewBox="26.0651838 -9.28833 10.034 11.5564" width="10.034pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,26.115,0)"><path d="M387 375C387 402 357 448 257 448C172 448 82 404 82 326C82 289 108 255 156 241V239C85 223 23 181 23 116C23 39 89 -12 182 -12C265 -12 336 31 378 91L361 114C320 73 269 47 216 47C157 47 115 82 115 137C115 191 160 219 218 219C243 219 262 218 272 217L304 259L302 266C295 265 281 264 255 264C195 264 163 294 163 335C163 377 200 416 249 416C293 416 321 389 329 342C331 332 335 329 341 329C355 329 387 352 387 375Z" id="g113-247"></path></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,31.446,0)"><path d="M275 270C275 450 212 609 64 710L45 686C145 604 203 442 203 270S147 -63 45 -147L64 -170C213 -68 275 89 275 270Z" id="g113-42"></path></g></svg></span> that cannot be assessed by these authors.</p><p>So, when we come to a singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem of small time lag, the following researchers address the case which works only for small time lag. In [<a href="#B17">17</a>], the authors used the backward Euler scheme for temporal discretization and a central difference scheme with an adaptive mesh selection strategy for spatial discretization. In [<a href="#B18">18</a>], the authors used the Euler method to discretize the time derivative and a B-spline collocation scheme for the spatial discretization on a uniform mesh. In this paper, both small and large time delays are considered, and the developed scheme is first-order convergent. In [<a href="#B19">19</a>], the scheme is developed using the backward Euler method in the discretization of the time derivative, and a higher-order finite difference method is employed for the approximation of the spatial derivative. In this scheme, an exponential fitting factor is introduced, and the resulting scheme is first-order convergent.</p><p>From these, we are motivated to construct and analyze a higher order <span class="nowrap"><svg height="6.1673pt" id="M2" style="vertical-align:-0.2063904pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -5.96091 5.44961 6.1673" width="5.44961pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-247"></use></g></svg>-</span>uniform numerical scheme, for the problem considered in [<a href="#B17">17</a>]. The proposed hybrid scheme is a combination of the cubic spline method and the midpoint upwind scheme on piecewise Shishkin mesh in the spatial direction and the Crank-Nicolson method in the temporal direction. The advantage of the present method over the other methods in [<a href="#B17">17</a>–<a href="#B19">19</a>] is that it is a second-order accurate in both time and space variables, as well as its accuracy. In addition, in the paper [<a href="#B17">17</a>–<a href="#B19">19</a>], Taylor’s series expansion is applied at the beginning without any restriction on the domain. In such a case, the advantage of the interval condition for the delay term in the approximation is meaningless. So we incorporate the condition where Taylor’s series expansion is applied without losing the interval condition.</p><p>Notations: all through this paper, <svg height="8.8423pt" id="M3" style="vertical-align:-0.2064009pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -8.6359 8.8162 8.8423" width="8.8162pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)"><path d="M645 631C614 643 545 666 457 666C215 666 23 519 23 283C23 90 158 -16 337 -16C412 -16 489 2 522 10C543 39 590 127 606 167L580 181C519 89 459 18 348 18C201 18 122 136 122 287C122 464 244 632 435 632C544 632 602 595 608 472L639 475C643 526 645 581 645 631Z" id="g113-68"></path></g></svg> and its subscripts denote generic positive constants independent of the perturbation parameter <svg height="6.1673pt" id="M4" style="vertical-align:-0.2063904pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -5.96091 5.44961 6.1673" width="5.44961pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-247"></use></g></svg> and mesh sizes. Also, <svg height="11.439pt" id="M5" style="vertical-align:-2.15067pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -9.28833 21.4778 11.439" width="21.4778pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)"><path d="M162 -163V703H102V-163H162ZM309 -163V703H249V-163H309Z" id="g113-10"></path></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,15.977,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-10"></use></g></svg> denotes the standard supremum norm, defined as <span class="inline_break"><svg height="25.9596pt" id="M6" 76C680 141 743 248 743 375ZM644 379C644 188 520 36 305 36C277 36 249 38 229 46C205 55 202 71 212 126L293 553C300 588 306 600 317 606C330 613 356 617 390 617C547 617 644 537 644 379Z" id="g113-69"></path></g></svg>.</span></p><h4 id="problem-formulation">2. Problem Formulation</h4><p>Consider the following singularly perturbed delay parabolic problem [<a href="#B17">17</a>, <a href="#B19">19</a>]:
<span class="equation_break" id="EEq1"><span class="left_break" id="L9"></span><span class="middle_break"><span class="center_break" id="M9"><svg height="29.5311pt" id="M9-1" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 120.377 29.5311" width="120.377pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g id="B9-1"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,11.591)"><path d="M471 379C471 Hence, the minimum of <svg height="14.2771pt" id="M106" style="vertical-align:-2.502999pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -11.7741 36.7244 14.2771" width="36.7244pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-236"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.0091,0,0,-0.0091,5.825,-5.741)"><use xlink:href="#g50-107"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.0091,0,0,-0.0091,9.739,-5.741)"><use xlink:href="#g54-36"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.0091,0,0,-0.0091,15.299,-5.741)"><use xlink:href="#g50-50"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,20.28,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-41"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,24.778,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-121"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,32.046,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-42"></use></g></svg> is nonnegative.</span></p><p>To prove that the approach is <span class="nowrap"><svg height="6.1673pt" id="M107" style="vertical-align:-0.2063904pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -5.96091 5.44961 6.1673" width="5.44961pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-247"></use></g></svg>-</span>uniform, more specific information on the behavior of the exact solution is required. This is done by decomposing the solution <span class="inline_break"><svg height="11.5564pt" id="M108" style="vertical-align:-2.26807pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -9.28833 21.724 11.5564" transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,18.76,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-45"></use></g></svg><span class="ipunc"></span><svg height="11.5564pt" style="vertical-align:-2.26807pt" version="1.1" xlink:href="#g113-117"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,28.336,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-42"></use></g></svg></span> into a smooth component <svg height="9.10848pt" id="M109" Discretization in the Spatial Direction</h5><h6 id="sec4.2.1">4.2.1. Shishkin Mesh</h6><p>The piecewise-uniform mesh having <span class="inline_break"><svg height="9.75571pt" id="M113" style="vertical-align:-1.11981pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -8.6359 22.173 xlink:href="#g190-41"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,4.5,9.26)"><use xlink:href="#g190-166"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,11.14,9.26)"><use xlink:href="#g190-166"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,17.6,9.26)"><use xlink:href="#g190-42"></use></g></g></svg><svg class="alt_label" height="213.206pt" id="IL164" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 22.18 213.206" width="22.18pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><use transform="matrix(1 0 0 1 0 100.67)" xlink:href="#B164-2"></use></svg></span></span></p><h6 id="sec4.4.1">4.4.1. Hybrid Scheme</h6><p>The upwind scheme is stable and produces a first-order accurate solution [<a href="#B27">27</a>–<a href="#B29">29</a>]. The cubic spline method satisfies the discrete maximum norm only in the fine mesh region, whereas in the coarse mesh region, the solution is unstable [<a href="#B28">28</a>, <a href="#B29">29</a>]. The benefit of constructing a hybrid scheme is that it gives higher-order parameter uniform convergent schemes that are oscillation-free across the region. So, using a piecewise-uniform Shishkin mesh, we develop a second-order parameter uniform convergent scheme that combines the cubic spline approach in the fine mesh region and the midpoint upwind scheme in the coarse mesh region. Thus, the discrete problem of (<a href="#EEq1">1</a>) is given by

transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,10.73,9.26)"><use xlink:href="#g190-254"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,17.14,9.26)"><use xlink:href="#g190-42"></use></g></g></svg><svg class="alt_label" height="203.81pt" id="IL281" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 21.72 203.81" width="21.72pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><use transform="matrix(1 0 0 1 0 95.97)" xlink:href="#B281-9"></use></svg></span></span></span></p><h4 id="conclusion">7. Conclusion</h4><p>A singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem of small time lag is treated, via a hybrid fitted mesh scheme for the space discretization and the Crank–Nicolson method on a uniform mesh for time derivative. Due to the presence of a small perturbation parameter, the problem exhibits the left side boundary layer at <span class="inline_break"><svg height="8.55521pt" id="M282" style="vertical-align:-0.2063904pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -8.34882 18.53 8.55521" width="18.53pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-121"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,10.899,0)"><use xlink:href="#g117-34"></use></g></svg><span class="irelop"></span><span class="nowrap"><svg height="8.55521pt" style="vertical-align:-0.2063904pt" version="1.1" viewBox="22.1121838 -8.34882 6.419 8.55521" width="6.419pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,22.162,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-49"></use></g></svg>.</span></span> Figures <a href="fig1/" target="_blank">1</a>, <a href="fig2/#b" target="_blank">2(b)</a>, <a href="fig3/" target="_blank">3</a>, and <a href="fig4/#b" target="_blank">4(b)</a> of the surface plot and one-dimensional plot for the numerical solution of the problems in Example <a href="#ex1">1</a> and Example <a href="#ex2">2</a> clearly demonstrate the behavior of the boundary layer as <span class="inline_break"><svg height="8.55521pt" id="M283" style="vertical-align:-0.2063904pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -8.34882 27.141 8.55521" width="27.141pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-247"></use></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,8.963,0)"><path d="M567 230V280H69V230H567Z" id="g117-149"></path></g><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,14.739,0)"><path d="M901 255C861 290 790 361 716 442L694 427L796 280H69V230H796L694 83L716 68C790 149 861 220 901 255Z" id="g117-148"></path></g></svg><span class="irelop"></span><span class="nowrap"><svg height="8.55521pt" style="vertical-align:-0.2063904pt" version="1.1" viewBox="30.800183800000003 -8.34882 6.382 8.55521" width="6.382pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,30.85,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-49"></use></g></svg>.</span></span> The maximum point-wise error of Example <a href="#ex1">1</a> and Example <a href="#ex2">2</a> is plotted in Figures <a href="fig2/#a" target="_blank">2(a)</a> and <a href="fig4/#a" target="_blank">4(a)</a>, respectively, in the log-log plot. The error analysis of the proposed scheme is proved, and the proposed scheme is second order <span class="nowrap"><svg height="6.1673pt" id="M284" style="vertical-align:-0.2063904pt" version="1.1" viewBox="-0.0498162 -5.96091 5.44961 6.1673" width="5.44961pt" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g transform="matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)"><use xlink:href="#g113-247"></use></g></svg>-</span>uniform convergent. The numerical results in Tables <a href="tab1/" target="_blank">1</a> and <a href="tab2/" target="_blank">2</a> of Example <a href="#ex1">1</a> and Example <a href="#ex2">2</a>, respectively, confirm that the tabulated numerical results are in agreement with the theoretical error estimates. In addition, we observed that the proposed scheme is more accurate and gives a higher rate of convergence as compared to some studies available in the literature. Since the approach is mesh dependent, when the number of mesh points increases, the effectiveness of the proposed scheme also increases. Due to the time limitations, we only discuss small time delays; however, with some slight adjustments, the scheme can also work for large time delays.</p><div class="partial-carousel-wrapper"><div Issues","route":"/publish-research/editors/special-issues"}]}]}]}},"subcode":"aaa","article":{"abstract":"In this article, a singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem with a small time lag is examined. Because of the appearance of a small perturbation parameter, a boundary layer is observed in the solution of the problem. A hybrid scheme has been constructed, which is a combination of the cubic spline method in the boundary layer region and the midpoint upwind scheme in the outer layer region on a piecewise Shishkin mesh in the spatial direction. For the discretization of the time derivative, the Crank-Nicolson method is used. Error analysis of the proposed method has been performed. We found that the proposed scheme is second-order convergent. Numerical examples are given, and the numerical results are in agreement with the theoretical results. Comparisons are made, and the results of the proposed scheme give more accurate solutions and a higher rate of convergence as compared to some previous findings available in the literature.","academicEditors":[{"surName":"Kumar","userId":0,"givenName":"Devendra"}],"guestEditors":[],"affiliations":[{"domainName":"bdu.edu.et","country":"Ethiopia","addrLines":[{"addrLine1":"Department of Mathematics","addrLine2":"College of Sciences","addrLine3":"Bahir Dar University","addrLine4":"Bahir Dar"}],"affId":1,"sup":1}],"articleId":"4382780","articleTitle":"Hybrid Fitted Numerical Scheme for Singularly Perturbed Convection-Diffusion Problem with a Small Time Lag","articleTitleToc":"Hybrid Fitted Numerical Scheme for Singularly Perturbed Convection-Diffusion Problem with a Small Time Lag","authors":[{"orcid":"https://orcid.org/0000-0003-4964-8193","givenName":"Mulunesh Amsalu","affSup":[{"affId":1}],"authorsListId":1,"surName":"Ayele","userId":0},{"authorsListId":2,"userId":0,"corresp":true,"orcid":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2548-3278","givenName":"Awoke Andargie","affSup":[{"affId":1}],"surName":"Tiruneh","email":"awoke248@yahoo.com"},{"orcid":"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-8205-4277","givenName":"Getachew Adamu","affSup":[{"affId":1}],"authorsListId":3,"surName":"Derese","userId":0}],"copyrightHolder":"Copyright \u0026#x00A9; Roos","refJournal":"Applied Numerical Mathematics","refId":27,"refTag":"27","refEid":"2-s2.0-0031141256","refTitle":"The midpoint upwind scheme","refDoi":"10.1016/S0168-9274(96)00071-2","refLastPage":"374","refVolume":"23","refText":"M. Stynes and H.-G. Roos, “The midpoint upwind scheme,” \u003ci\u003eApplied Numerical Mathematics\u003c/i\u003e, vol. 23, no. 3, pp. 361–374, 1997.","refNumber":"3","refFirstPage":"361"},{"refJournal":"Journal of Applied and Computational Mechanics","refId":28,"refTag":"28","refTitle":"A parameter uniform numerical scheme for singularly perturbed differential-difference equations with mixed shifts","refLastPage":"356","refYear":"2020","refVolume":"6","refText":"P. Mushahary, S. Sahu, and J. Mohapatra, “A parameter uniform numerical scheme for singularly perturbed differential-difference equations with mixed shifts,” \u003ci\u003eJournal of Applied and Computational Mechanics\u003c/i\u003e, vol. 6, no. 2, pp. 344–356, 2020.","refType":"journal","refNumber":"2","refFirstPage":"344","refAuthors":"P. Mushahary, S. Sahu, and J. Mohapatra"},{"refYear":"2009","refType":"journal","refAuthors":"R. K. Bawa and S. Natesan","refJournal":"International Journal of Computer Mathematics","refId":29,"refTag":"29","refEid":"2-s2.0-57349174596","refTitle":"An efficient hybrid numerical scheme for convection-dominated boundary-value problems","refDoi":"10.1080/00207160801955678","refLastPage":"273","refVolume":"86","refText":"R. K. Bawa and S. Natesan, “An efficient hybrid numerical scheme for convection-dominated boundary-value problems,” \u003ci\u003eInternational Journal of Computer Mathematics\u003c/i\u003e, vol. 86, no. 2, pp. 261–273, 2009.","refNumber":"2","refFirstPage":"261"}],"refUrl":"files.hindawi.com/journals/aaa/2023/4382780.enw","spotcheck":"yes","spotcheckPassed":"yes","supplementaryEmbedded":"no","type":"Research Article","updatedTimestamp":"2023-04-11 12:06:03","volume":2023,"sectionLinks":[{"title":"Abstract","hash":"abstract"},{"title":"Introduction","hash":"introduction"},{"title":"Problem Formulation","hash":"problem-formulation"},{"title":"Bounds on the Solution and Its Derivatives","hash":"bounds-on-the-solution-and-its-derivatives"},{"title":"Numerical Scheme","hash":"numerical-scheme"},{"title":"Stability and Error Analysis","hash":"stability-and-error-analysis"},{"title":"Numerical Illustration","hash":"numerical-illustration"},{"title":"Conclusion","hash":"conclusion"},{"title":"Data Availability","hash":"data-availability"},{"title":"Conflicts of Interest","hash":"conflicts-of-interest"},{"title":"References","hash":"references"},{"title":"Copyright","hash":"copyright"},{"title":"Related Articles","hash":"related-articles"}],"styleSheetUrl":"https://static.hindawi.com/articles/aaa/volume-2023/4382780/4382780-style.css","body":"\u003cdiv class=\"xml-content\"\u003e\u003ch4 class=\"header\" id=\"abstract\"\u003eAbstract\u003c/h4\u003e\u003cp\u003eIn this article, a singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem with a small time lag is examined. Because of the appearance of a small perturbation parameter, a boundary layer is observed in the solution of the problem. A hybrid scheme has been constructed, which is a combination of the cubic spline method in the boundary layer region and the midpoint upwind scheme in the outer layer region on a piecewise Shishkin mesh in the spatial direction. For the discretization of the time derivative, the Crank-Nicolson method is used. Error analysis of the proposed method has been performed. We found that the proposed scheme is second-order convergent. Numerical examples are given, and the numerical results are in agreement with the theoretical results. Comparisons are made, and the results of the proposed scheme give more accurate solutions and a higher rate of convergence as compared to some previous findings available in the literature.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cspan class=\"end-abs\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003ch4 id=\"introduction\"\u003e1. Introduction\u003c/h4\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe delay differential equations are versatile in mathematical modeling of processes where they provide a realistic simulation of the real-world phenomena. The real-world operations/interactions that take time to complete can be utilized to simulate the time lag experience such as gestation time, incubation period, and transportation delays. In the model, if a small parameter multiplies the highest order derivative term, involving at least one shift term in the temporal variable, we call it singularly perturbed time delay differential equations (SPTDDE). These problems arise in the varied area of science and engineering models, for instance, in population dynamics, in epidemiology, in respiratory system, and in tumor growth [\u003ca href=\"#B1\"\u003e1\u003c/a\u003e–\u003ca href=\"#B6\"\u003e6\u003c/a\u003e]. For more additional models, one can refer [\u003ca href=\"#B7\"\u003e7\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"#B8\"\u003e8\u003c/a\u003e]. Due to the appearance of the boundary layer in the solution of a singularly perturbed differential equation, classical numerical methods on equidistant grids are inadequate and fail to provide a reliable approximation, when the perturbation parameter tends to zero, unless otherwise, if one uses an unacceptably large number of grid points. Several articles have been written on the solution method for singularly perturbed delay differential equations, to cite a few [\u003ca href=\"#B9\"\u003e9\u003c/a\u003e–\u003ca href=\"#B13\"\u003e13\u003c/a\u003e]. Among the recently conducted studies on SPTDDE of the convection-diffusion type, having a right end boundary layer, in [\u003ca href=\"#B14\"\u003e14\u003c/a\u003e], the authors used an implicit-trapezoidal scheme on uniform mesh for temporal discretization, and for spatial discretization, a hybrid scheme, which is a combination of the midpoint upwind scheme and the central difference scheme on Shishkin type meshes, is applied. In [\u003ca href=\"#B8\"\u003e8\u003c/a\u003e], the scheme is constructed using the Crank-Nicolson method for temporal discretization, and a midpoint upwind finite difference scheme on a fitted piecewise-uniform mesh in spatial discretization is applied. In [\u003ca href=\"#B15\"\u003e15\u003c/a\u003e], the scheme is devised using backward Euler’s scheme on uniform mesh for temporal discretization and a new stable finite difference scheme on Shishkin mesh for spatial discretization. In [\u003ca href=\"#B16\"\u003e16\u003c/a\u003e], the problem is solved using the Crank-Nicolson method in temporal discretization, and in the spatial discretization, an exponentially fitted operator finite difference method on uniform mesh is used. All these developed schemes can work for both small and large time delays. However, except [\u003ca href=\"#B14\"\u003e14\u003c/a\u003e], the results of the above studies are first-order convergent, and there are some exceptional properties which work only for a small time delay \u003cspan class=\"inline_break\"\u003e\u003csvg height=\"11.5564pt\" id=\"M1\" style=\"vertical-align:-2.26807pt\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"-0.0498162 -9.28833 22.483 11.5564\" -12 190 -12C244 -12 288 5 328 33C406 87 444 170 444 249C444 329 404 391 331 475C265 550 222 605 222 627C222 647 238 657 267 657C355 657 421 585 484 499L494 514ZM359 234C359 143 319 30 219 30C172 30 class=\"irelop\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003csvg height=\"11.5564pt\" style=\"vertical-align:-2.26807pt\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"26.0651838 -9.28833 10.034 11.5564\" width=\"10.034pt\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\"\u003e\u003cg transform=\"matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,26.115,0)\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M387 375C387 402 357 448 257 448C172 448 82 404 82 326C82 289 108 255 156 241V239C85 223 23 181 23 116C23 39 89 -12 182 -12C265 -12 336 31 378 91L361 114C320 73 269 47 216 47C157 47 115 82 115 137C115 191 160 219 218 219C243 219 262 218 id=\"g113-247\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003cg transform=\"matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,31.446,0)\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M275 270C275 450 212 609 64 710L45 686C145 604 203 442 203 270S147 -63 45 -147L64 -170C213 -68 275 89 275 270Z\" id=\"g113-42\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003c/span\u003e that cannot be assessed by these authors.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eSo, when we come to a singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem of small time lag, the following researchers address the case which works only for small time lag. In [\u003ca href=\"#B17\"\u003e17\u003c/a\u003e], the authors used the backward Euler scheme for temporal discretization and a central difference scheme with an adaptive mesh selection strategy for spatial discretization. In [\u003ca href=\"#B18\"\u003e18\u003c/a\u003e], the authors used the Euler method to discretize the time derivative and a B-spline collocation scheme for the spatial discretization on a uniform mesh. In this paper, both small and large time delays are considered, and the developed scheme is first-order convergent. In [\u003ca href=\"#B19\"\u003e19\u003c/a\u003e], the scheme is developed using the backward Euler method in the discretization of the time derivative, and a higher-order finite difference method is employed for the approximation of the spatial derivative. In this scheme, an exponential fitting factor is introduced, and the resulting scheme is first-order convergent.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eFrom these, we are motivated to construct and analyze a higher order \u003cspan class=\"nowrap\"\u003e\u003csvg height=\"6.1673pt\" id=\"M2\" style=\"vertical-align:-0.2063904pt\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"-0.0498162 -5.96091 5.44961 6.1673\" width=\"5.44961pt\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\"\u003e\u003cg transform=\"matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#g113-247\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e-\u003c/span\u003euniform numerical scheme, for the problem considered in [\u003ca href=\"#B17\"\u003e17\u003c/a\u003e]. The proposed hybrid scheme is a combination of the cubic spline method and the midpoint upwind scheme on piecewise Shishkin mesh in the spatial direction and the Crank-Nicolson method in the temporal direction. The advantage of the present method over the other methods in [\u003ca href=\"#B17\"\u003e17\u003c/a\u003e–\u003ca href=\"#B19\"\u003e19\u003c/a\u003e] is that it is a second-order accurate in both time and space variables, as well as its accuracy. In addition, in the paper [\u003ca href=\"#B17\"\u003e17\u003c/a\u003e–\u003ca href=\"#B19\"\u003e19\u003c/a\u003e], Taylor’s series expansion is applied at the beginning without any restriction on the domain. In such a case, the advantage of the interval condition for the delay term in the approximation is meaningless. So we incorporate the condition where Taylor’s series expansion is applied without losing the interval condition.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eNotations: all through this paper, \u003csvg height=\"8.8423pt\" id=\"M3\" style=\"vertical-align:-0.2064009pt\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"-0.0498162 -8.6359 8.8162 8.8423\" width=\"8.8162pt\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\"\u003e\u003cg transform=\"matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M645 631C614 643 545 666 457 666C215 666 23 519 23 283C23 90 158 -16 337 -16C412 -16 489 2 522 10C543 39 590 127 606 167L580 181C519 89 459 18 348 18C201 18 122 136 122 287C122 464 244 632 435 632C544 632 602 595 608 472L639 475C643 526 645 581 645 631Z\" id=\"g113-68\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e and its subscripts denote generic positive constants independent of the perturbation parameter \u003csvg height=\"6.1673pt\" id=\"M4\" style=\"vertical-align:-0.2063904pt\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"-0.0498162 -5.96091 5.44961 6.1673\" width=\"5.44961pt\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\"\u003e\u003cg transform=\"matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#g113-247\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e and mesh sizes. Also, \u003csvg height=\"11.439pt\" id=\"M5\" style=\"vertical-align:-2.15067pt\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"-0.0498162 -9.28833 21.4778 11.439\" width=\"21.4778pt\" transform=\"matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,258.66,198.322)\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#g113-47\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003csvg class=\"alt_equation\" xlink:href=\"#g190-42\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003csvg class=\"alt_label\" height=\"213.206pt\" id=\"IL164\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 22.18 213.206\" width=\"22.18pt\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\"\u003e\u003cuse transform=\"matrix(1 0 0 1 0 100.67)\" xlink:href=\"#B164-2\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch6 id=\"sec4.4.1\"\u003e4.4.1. Hybrid Scheme\u003c/h6\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe upwind scheme is stable and produces a first-order accurate solution [\u003ca href=\"#B27\"\u003e27\u003c/a\u003e–\u003ca href=\"#B29\"\u003e29\u003c/a\u003e]. The cubic spline method satisfies the discrete maximum norm only in the fine mesh region, whereas in the coarse mesh region, the solution is unstable [\u003ca href=\"#B28\"\u003e28\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"#B29\"\u003e29\u003c/a\u003e]. The benefit of constructing a hybrid scheme is that it gives higher-order parameter uniform convergent schemes that are oscillation-free across the region. So, using a piecewise-uniform Shishkin mesh, we develop a second-order parameter uniform convergent scheme that combines the cubic spline approach in the fine mesh region and the midpoint upwind scheme in the coarse mesh region. transform=\"matrix(1 0 0 1 0 95.97)\" xlink:href=\"#B281-9\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003ch4 id=\"conclusion\"\u003e7. Conclusion\u003c/h4\u003e\u003cp\u003eA singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem of small time lag is treated, via a hybrid fitted mesh scheme for the space discretization and the Crank–Nicolson method on a uniform mesh for time derivative. Due to the presence of a small perturbation parameter, the problem exhibits the left side boundary layer at \u003cspan class=\"inline_break\"\u003e\u003csvg height=\"8.55521pt\" id=\"M282\" demonstrate the behavior of the boundary layer as \u003cspan class=\"inline_break\"\u003e\u003csvg height=\"8.55521pt\" id=\"M283\" style=\"vertical-align:-0.2063904pt\" version=\"1.1\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\"\u003e\u003cg transform=\"matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,30.85,0)\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#g113-49\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e The maximum point-wise error of Example \u003ca href=\"#ex1\"\u003e1\u003c/a\u003e and Example \u003ca href=\"#ex2\"\u003e2\u003c/a\u003e is plotted in Figures \u003ca href=\"fig2/#a\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e2(a)\u003c/a\u003e and \u003ca href=\"fig4/#a\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e4(a)\u003c/a\u003e, respectively, in the log-log plot. The error analysis of the proposed scheme is proved, and the proposed scheme is second order \u003cspan class=\"nowrap\"\u003e\u003csvg height=\"6.1673pt\" id=\"M284\" style=\"vertical-align:-0.2063904pt\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"-0.0498162 -5.96091 5.44961 6.1673\" width=\"5.44961pt\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\"\u003e\u003cg transform=\"matrix(.013,0,0,-0.013,0,0)\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#g113-247\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e-\u003c/span\u003euniform convergent. The numerical results in Tables \u003ca href=\"tab1/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e1\u003c/a\u003e and \u003ca href=\"tab2/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e2\u003c/a\u003e of Example \u003ca href=\"#ex1\"\u003e1\u003c/a\u003e and Example \u003ca href=\"#ex2\"\u003e2\u003c/a\u003e, respectively, confirm that the tabulated numerical results are in agreement with the theoretical error estimates. In addition, we observed that the proposed scheme is more accurate and gives a higher rate of convergence as compared to some studies available in the literature. Since the approach is mesh dependent, when the number of mesh points increases, the effectiveness of the proposed scheme also increases. Due to the time limitations, we only discuss small time delays; however, with some slight adjustments, the scheme can also work for large time delays.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv with a Small Time Lag","metaDescription":"In this article, a singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem with a small time lag is examined. Because of the appearance of a small perturbation parameter, a boundary layer is observed in the solution of the problem. A hybrid scheme has been constructed, which is a combination of the cubic spline method in the boundary layer region and the midpoint upwind scheme in the outer layer region on a piecewise Shishkin mesh in the spatial direction. For the discretization of the time derivative, the Crank-Nicolson method is used. Error analysis of the proposed method has been performed. We found that the proposed scheme is second-order convergent. Numerical examples are given, and the numerical results are in agreement with the theoretical results. Comparisons are made, and the results of the proposed scheme give more accurate solutions and a higher rate of convergence as compared to some previous findings available in the literature.","metaTwitter":{"metaCardTwitter":"summary_large_image","metaTitleTwitter":"Hybrid Fitted Numerical Scheme for Singularly Perturbed Convection-Diffusion Problem with a Small Time Lag","metaDescriptionTwitter":"In this article, a singularly perturbed convection-diffusion problem with a small time lag is examined.
